    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Telegrafbukta is a sandy public beach located at the southern tip of Tromsøya island, approximately 2.5 kilometres from Tromsø city centre. The beach faces west across the Tromsø strait toward the Lyngen Alps — a mountain range on the mainland peninsula that rises to over 1,800 metres. <strong>The clear westward orientation makes Telegrafbukta the best free ground-level viewpoint in Tromsø for watching the midnight sun</strong> sit on the horizon at midnight during the summer season (approximately 20 May to 22 July). The beach is a consistent gathering point for local residents and visitors during the midnight sun period.</p>
    <p>The beach consists of sandy and pebbled sections bordered by low coastal vegetation. The adjacent Telegrafbukta area includes parkland, maintained walking and cycling paths running along the waterfront, and connects to the broader coastal trail network on the southern part of Tromsøya. <strong>The Tromsø University Museum (Norges arktiske universitetsmuseum) is approximately 300 metres to the north</strong>, and the museum's Café Rotunden is the nearest indoor facility. Bus number 33 from the city centre stops directly at Telegrafbukta; bus number 40 stops at the Tromsø Museum stop approximately 300 metres away.</p>
    <p>Water temperatures in the Tromsø strait reach approximately 14–17°C in July and August, sufficient for swimming and wading. <strong>There is no lifeguard service, no changing rooms, and no paid facilities at the beach itself</strong>. The beach is accessible year-round and used by cold-water swimmers and winter walkers outside the summer season. It is also visible in the context of Northern Lights viewing during the aurora season (September to March), as the open western horizon reduces obstructions. No entry fee, ticket, or booking is required at any time.</p>
  </div>

